<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<pretext xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">

	<docinfo/>

	<article xml:id="workshop-quick-reference">
		<title>PreTeXt Workshop — Quick Reference</title>

		<introduction>
			<p>
				<em>Everything you need during today's session. Keep this page open in a tab.</em>
			</p>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Before You Start</title>
				<p>
					Make sure you are signed in to <c>github.com</c> in your browser.
					Then open the workshop template repository at:
				</p>
				<p>
					<url href="https://github.com/PreTeXtBook/pretext-codespace">
						<c>github.com/PreTeXtBook/pretext-codespace</c>
					</url>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</introduction>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 1: Launch Codespace first                  -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="launch-codespace">
			<title>1. Launch Your Codespace First</title>

			<p>
				<em>Important: we start your Codespace now and then leave it alone for about half an hour.
				First-time setup takes 5–10 minutes, so while it boots in the background we will practice
				PreTeXt in a sandbox. Do not close the Codespace tab.</em>
			</p>

			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						On the <c>pretext-codespace</c> page, click the green
						<term>Use this template</term> button (top right), then choose
						<term>Create a new repository</term>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Give your repository a name (for example, <c>my-pretext-workshop</c>),
						leave it set to <term>Public</term>, and click
						<term>Create repository from template</term>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						On your new repository page, click the green <c>&lt; &gt; Code</c> button,
						switch to the <term>Codespaces</term> tab, and click
						<term>Create codespace on main</term>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						A new tab opens and begins building your workspace.
						<em>Leave this tab open. Do not touch it.</em>
						It will finish on its own while you work in the sandbox.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Open a <em>new browser tab</em> and go to
						<url href="https://pretext.plus/tryit"><c>pretext.plus/tryit</c></url>.
						Keep both tabs open for the rest of the workshop.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>

			<assemblage>
				<title>✓ You know step 1 worked when…</title>
				<p>
					<ul>
						<li>Your Codespace tab is visibly loading or says <q>Setting up your codespace.</q></li>
						<li>You can see the <c>pretext.plus/tryit</c> editor in a different tab.</li>
						<li>You are not tempted to click around in the Codespace tab.</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 2: Sandbox exercises                       -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="sandbox-exercises">
			<title>2. While You Wait — Practice in the Sandbox</title>

			<p>
				<em><c>pretext.plus/tryit</c> is a throwaway sandbox. You type PreTeXt source on
				the left, click <term>Rebuild</term>, and see the result on the right. Nothing you
				do here is saved — that is fine. Every exercise below is in this handout, so you
				can always paste it again.</em>
			</p>

			<p>
				<alert>How to work each exercise:</alert> find the closing <c>&lt;/section&gt;</c>
				tag near the bottom of the sandbox, and paste the snippet on a new line
				<em>just above it</em>. Then click <term>Rebuild</term> and look at the preview.
			</p>

			<subsection xml:id="exercise-1">
				<title>Exercise 1 — A paragraph with inline math</title>
				<p>
					<em>Paste this inside the section and rebuild. Notice how inline math
					flows with the text.</em>
				</p>
				<program language="xml">
					<code>
<![CDATA[<p>The Pythagorean theorem states that <m>a^2 + b^2 = c^2</m>,
where <m>c</m> is the length of the hypotenuse.</p>]]>
					</code>
				</program>
			</subsection>

			<subsection xml:id="exercise-2">
				<title>Exercise 2 — A definition</title>
				<p>
					<em>Add a formal definition. The <c>xml:id</c> is a label we will use in Exercise 5.</em>
				</p>
				<program language="xml">
					<code>
<![CDATA[<definition xml:id="def-right-triangle">
  <statement>
    <p>A <term>right triangle</term> is a triangle
    with one angle measuring exactly 90 degrees.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>]]>
					</code>
				</program>
			</subsection>

			<subsection xml:id="exercise-3">
				<title>Exercise 3 — An example</title>
				<p>
					<em>Examples get numbered automatically. Try changing the title after you rebuild.</em>
				</p>
				<program language="xml">
					<code>
<![CDATA[<example>
  <title>A 3-4-5 triangle</title>
  <statement>
    <p>Show that a triangle with sides 3, 4, and 5
    is a right triangle.</p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>Check: <m>3^2 + 4^2 = 9 + 16 = 25 = 5^2</m>.</p>
  </solution>
</example>]]>
					</code>
				</program>
			</subsection>

			<subsection xml:id="exercise-4">
				<title>Exercise 4 — An exercise</title>
				<p>
					<em>Exercises are also numbered automatically, separately from examples.</em>
				</p>
				<program language="xml">
					<code>
<![CDATA[<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>Find the length of the hypotenuse of a right
    triangle with legs of length 5 and 12.</p>
  </statement>
</exercise>]]>
					</code>
				</program>
			</subsection>

			<subsection xml:id="exercise-5">
				<title>Exercise 5 — A cross-reference</title>
				<p>
					<em>This is the magic moment. The <c>&lt;xref&gt;</c> points at the <c>xml:id</c>
					you gave the definition in Exercise 2, and PreTeXt builds a working link for you.</em>
				</p>
				<program language="xml">
					<code>
<![CDATA[<p>For a reminder of the terminology,
see <xref ref="def-right-triangle"/>.</p>]]>
					</code>
				</program>
			</subsection>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Finished early?</title>
				<p>
					Try changing the title of your example. Swap the numbers in the 3-4-5 example
					for a 5-12-13 triangle. Try breaking something on purpose to see what an error
					looks like. The sandbox is for playing.
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 3: Back to Codespace                       -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="back-to-codespace">
			<title>3. Back to Your Codespace</title>

			<p>
				<em>Your Codespace should be ready now. Switch to that tab — you should see a
				file explorer on the left and a blue bar at the bottom of the window.</em>
			</p>

			<ol>
				<li>
					<p>
						Press <kbd>F1</kbd> (or <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>Shift</kbd>+<kbd>P</kbd>) to
						open the command palette. Type <c>pretext new</c> and select
						<term>PreTeXt: New Project</term>.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						When asked what kind of project, choose <term>book</term>. When asked where
						to put it, press <kbd>Enter</kbd> to accept the default location.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						The window reloads with a new project. Look for the <c>source</c> folder
						on the left and click to expand it.
					</p>
				</li>
				<li>
					<p>
						Find and open <c>main.ptx</c> (or the first chapter file in <c>source/</c>).
						This is where your lesson will live.
					</p>
				</li>
			</ol>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Codespace tab says it stopped or went to sleep?</title>
				<p>
					No problem — just click the button to resume it. Waking a sleeping Codespace takes
					a few seconds, not the full 5–10 minutes. Your work is still there.
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 4: Starter lesson                          -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="starter-lesson">
			<title>4. Make It Yours — Your Starter Lesson</title>

			<p>
				Inside <c>main.ptx</c>, find the first <c>&lt;section&gt;</c> inside the first
				<c>&lt;chapter&gt;</c>. Replace everything between the opening and closing
				<c>&lt;section&gt;</c> tags with the block below. Save the file
				(<kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>S</kbd>).
			</p>

			<program language="xml">
				<code>
<![CDATA[<title>Right Triangles</title>

<p>This short lesson introduces right triangles and
the Pythagorean theorem.</p>

<definition xml:id="def-right-triangle">
  <statement>
    <p>A <term>right triangle</term> is a triangle
    with one angle measuring exactly 90 degrees.</p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<p>The Pythagorean theorem states that
<m>a^2 + b^2 = c^2</m>, where <m>c</m> is the
length of the hypotenuse.</p>

<example>
  <title>A 3-4-5 triangle</title>
  <statement>
    <p>Show that a triangle with sides 3, 4, and 5
    is a right triangle.</p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>Check: <m>3^2 + 4^2 = 9 + 16 = 25 = 5^2</m>.</p>
  </solution>
</example>

<exercise>
  <statement>
    <p>Find the length of the hypotenuse of a right
    triangle with legs of length 5 and 12.</p>
  </statement>
</exercise>

<p>For a reminder of the terminology,
see <xref ref="def-right-triangle"/>.</p>]]>
				</code>
			</program>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Now make it yours</title>
				<p>
					Change the chapter title. Rename the section. Swap the topic for something you
					actually teach — replace the definition with your own, rewrite the example,
					change the exercise. The structure stays the same. The content is yours.
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 5: Build, View, Deploy                     -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="build-view-deploy">
			<title>5. Build, View, Deploy</title>

			<p>
				Find the <term>▷ PreTeXt</term> button in the blue bar at the very bottom of the
				Codespace window. That button is your control panel.
			</p>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Build — turn your source into a webpage</title>
				<p>
					Click <term>▷ PreTeXt</term> → <term>Build default target</term>. Wait for the
					terminal to finish. <em>You must Build again every time you change your source.</em>
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>View — preview your webpage</title>
				<p>
					Click <term>▷ PreTeXt</term> → <term>View</term>. A preview tab opens. After every
					edit, Build again and refresh the preview.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Deploy — publish to a public URL</title>
				<p>
					Click <term>▷ PreTeXt</term> → <term>Deploy</term>. Watch the terminal for your
					<c>github.io</c> link. It may take a few minutes after the command finishes before
					the site is actually live.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<assemblage>
				<title>✓ You're done when…</title>
				<p>
					<ul>
						<li>You have a <c>github.io</c> URL in the terminal.</li>
						<li>You can open that URL in a new tab and see your lesson.</li>
						<li>You are ready to share the link with a colleague.</li>
					</ul>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 6: Troubleshooting                         -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="troubleshooting">
			<title>6. If You Get Stuck</title>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Build failed with a red error</title>
				<p>
					Almost always a missing or mismatched tag. Look at the error message for a line
					number, and check that every <c>&lt;tag&gt;</c> has a matching <c>&lt;/tag&gt;</c>.
					When in doubt, paste the starter block again and edit more carefully.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Preview tab is blank, stale, or won't load</title>
				<p>
					Build again first, then refresh the preview tab. The preview does not update
					automatically. If that does not help, close the preview tab and run
					<term>▷ PreTeXt</term> → <term>View</term> again.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Codespace closed, timed out, or went to sleep</title>
				<p>
					Go back to your repository on <c>github.com</c>, click the <c>&lt; &gt; Code</c>
					button, open the <term>Codespaces</term> tab, and click your existing codespace
					to resume it. Your files are still there.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Something else is wrong</title>
				<p>
					Raise your hand. We will come to you. You are almost certainly not the only one.
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 7: LaTeX bridge                            -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="latex-bridge">
			<title>7. LaTeX → PreTeXt Cheat Sheet</title>

			<p>
				<em>If you already write LaTeX, most of what you know transfers directly. The math
				inside the tags is still LaTeX.</em>
			</p>

			<table>
				<title>Common LaTeX patterns and their PreTeXt equivalents</title>
				<tabular top="minor" bottom="minor" left="minor" halign="left">
					<col right="minor"/>
					<col right="minor"/>
					<row header="yes" bottom="minor">
						<cell><alert>LaTeX</alert></cell>
						<cell><alert>PreTeXt</alert></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\(x^2\)</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;m&gt;x^2&lt;/m&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\[ \int f \]</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;me&gt;\int f&lt;/me&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\section{Title}</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;section&gt;&lt;title&gt;Title&lt;/title&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\begin{itemize}</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;ul&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\item text</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;li&gt;&lt;p&gt;text&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/li&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\begin{definition}</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;definition&gt;&lt;statement&gt;&lt;p&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\emph{word}</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;em&gt;word&lt;/em&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\textbf{word}</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;term&gt;word&lt;/term&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
					<row>
						<cell><c>\ref{label}</c></cell>
						<cell><c>&lt;xref ref="label"/&gt;</c></cell>
					</row>
				</tabular>
			</table>
		</section>

		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<!-- Section 8: After the workshop                      -->
		<!-- ================================================= -->
		<section xml:id="after-workshop">
			<title>8. After the Workshop</title>

			<p>
				<em>Three ways to keep going, depending on how you like to work.</em>
			</p>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Keep using Codespaces (recommended)</title>
				<p>
					Your repository is yours. Come back anytime, open the Codespace from the
					<c>&lt; &gt; Code</c> button, and continue editing. Your lesson is already
					deployed, so re-running <term>Deploy</term> updates the live site.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Prefer not to use GitHub at all?</title>
				<p>
					PreTeXt.Plus offers a free tier at
					<url href="https://pretext.plus"><c>pretext.plus</c></url> that lets you
					create up to 10 projects with shareable links — no GitHub account required.
					It is a great fit for quick drafts and one-off documents. The same PreTeXt
					markup you learned today works there too.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Already have a pile of LaTeX?</title>
				<p>
					PreTeXt.Plus includes a LaTeX-to-PreTeXt converter. Treat its output as a
					<em>starting point</em> rather than a finished conversion — some things will
					need cleanup — but for a first look at how your existing material would feel
					in PreTeXt, it is a quick win.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Install PreTeXt locally (long-term)</title>
				<p>
					Eventually you may want PreTeXt running on your own machine. The official
					documentation at <url href="https://pretextbook.org"><c>pretextbook.org</c></url>
					walks through the options. No rush — the Codespaces workflow will serve you
					well for a long time.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<paragraphs>
				<title>Community and help</title>
				<p>
					The PreTeXt community is active and welcoming. Start at
					<url href="https://pretextbook.org/community.html"><c>pretextbook.org/community.html</c></url>
					for forums, documentation, and the author's guide.
				</p>
			</paragraphs>

			<p>
				<em>PreTeXt workshop · your Codespace and your published site will still be there tomorrow.</em>
			</p>
		</section>

	</article>
</pretext>
